audio.example:
&lt;p&gt;This audio has the controls, meaning it can be controlled. This is Battle is to the Strong by Yuki Kajiura.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;audio controls&gt;&lt;source src="assets/the_battle_is_to_the_strong.mp3" /&gt; Your browser does not support the audio element.&lt;/audio&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This audio has been muted with the muted attribute by default. Same music file, also has preload attribute which determines whether the element is preloaded, in this case preload is set to "none".&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;audio controls muted preload="none"&gt; &lt;source src="the_battle_is_to_the_strong.mp3" /&gt; &lt;/audio&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The looping audio has a loop applied. This is To Be Continued by Yuki Kajiura. &lt;/p&gt;&lt;audio controls loop&gt; &lt;source src="assets/to_be_continued.mp3" /&gt; Your browser does not support the audio element&lt;/audio&gt;

base.example:
&lt;base href="http://yahoo.com"/&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The base element specifies a base URL to use for all relative URLs in a document.
&lt;p&gt;For example, this link will link directly to a specific page.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;a href="https://www.google.com/search?q=base"&gt;https://www.google.com/search?q=base&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;br&gt;
&lt;p&gt;However, this link is only a relative URL. The base is set to a different website, which will redirect to a different host.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;a href="/search?q=base"&gt;/search?q=base&lt;/a&gt;

